AWS KMS returns an ECDSA signature encoded using ASN.1 DER.

The signature is a byte array with this structure:

30 <len>
   02 <rLen> <r bytes>
   02 <sLen> <s bytes>

index 0:
0x30 → ASN.1 SEQUENCE tag

index 1:
length of the sequence contents

index 2:
0x02 → INTEGER tag for R

index 3:
length of R in bytes

index 4..(4+rLen-1):
the bytes of R

After R, the next element begins:

02 <sLen> <s bytes>

The location of S depends on rLen, so we compute:

offset += 2 + rLen

Then we parse S the same way we parsed R.

We extract both integers into byte arrays.

Finally we convert the DER format into the JOSE format required by JWT,
which is simply:

[R (32 bytes)][S (32 bytes)]

If R or S are not exactly 32 bytes we normalize them by
removing leading zeros or padding with zeros.